metadata.label: Binding
metadata.value: Alum-tawed goatskin dyed red with Brazil wood over oak boards sewn on four supports. Conserved and rebound at Cambridge University Library by Shaun Thompson in 2014. The previous binding of pigskin by Stoakley (Cambridge, 1890) is stored with the manuscript.

metadata.label: Condition
metadata.value: The manuscript is generally in good condition. There is some staining, particularly to the edges of leaves, some holes and tears in the parchment, many of which bear traces of early repair; see for example the tears on fols 97 and 98 and the repair on fol. 135 which retains its original sewing thread.

metadata.label: Script
metadata.value: Written in Gothic textualis.

metadata.label: Origin Place
metadata.value: Thorney, Cambridgeshire

metadata.label: Provenance
metadata.value: In the possession of the Fane family, Earls of Westmorland from the seventeenth century, as evidenced by the inscriptions on fol. 11r. Lot 134 in the sale of 'a nobleman', i.e. Francis Fane, the twelfth Earl of Westmorland, at Sotheby's, 13 July 1887 and bought by Bernard Quaritch. No. 15 in Quaritch's Handlist of illuminated and historical manuscripts on exhibition ... 4-14 June 1889. Bought by Cambridge University Library from Quaritch 22 November 1890 with funds from the Rustat Benefaction and Samuel Sandars (1837-1894).

metadata.label: Physical Location
metadata.value: Cambridge University Library

metadata.label: Extent
metadata.value: iii + 203 + iii. Leaf height: 348 mm, width: 243 mm. Written height: 235 mm, width: 143 mm.

metadata.label: Abstract
metadata.value:
Thorney Abbey was the smallest of three fenland monasteries re-founded by Bishop Aethelwold in the tenth century. Virtually nothing is known about the management of its estates and the Red Book of Thorney (MSS Add. 3020 and 3021) is its sole surviving cartulary. Compiled in the early fourteenth century with later additions, many of which concern deeds omitted from the main sections, it is both elegant and, for the most part, highly organised. The main entries have contemporary folio and charter numbers in red ink, There are also headers and footers in red ink. Rubrics, again in red ink, indicate the subject matter of individual entries and also provide much incidental detail. The royal and topographical sections are divided into eight parts, followed by a ninth with miscellaneous fines, agreements and ecclesiastical documents, together with a particularly valuable De Gestis Abbatum. Annotations, contemporary and later, and cross references are frequent and indicate that the cartulary was designed to be used.

The cartulary as a whole contains transcriptions of material from before the Conquest to 1531, with a special wealth of thirteenth-century charters. Witness lists are given but not usually in full. The black ink entries in De Gestis Abbatum record a rich mixture of documents relating inter alia to estates, advowsons, fen disputes and grants to the convent. The red ink entries, which describe each abbacy, contain much information about elections, vacancies, building works and land dealings.

There is no printed edition of the cartulary. Its contents are examined in S. Raban, "The Estates of Thorney and Crowland", University of Cambridge, Department of Land Economy, Occasional Paper, 7 (1977) and S. G. Raban, The Property of Thorney and Crowland Abbeys (unpublished Cambridge PhD thesis, 1972).

Sandra Raban

metadata.value: Early fourteenth century. Original entries were compiled during the abbacy of William de Clapton (1305-1323).

metadata.label: Collation
metadata.value:
The MS consists of 20 quires as follows:

4 modern parchment flyleaves
Quire 110 (fols 1-10 plus additional parchment leaf (1a) and paper leaf (10a))
Quire 21 (fol. 11; stub of conjoint leaf after fol. 23)
Quire 312 (fols 12-23)
Quire 412 (fols 24-33; last two leaves cut out, stubs remain)
Quire 512 (fols 34-40e; leaves 8-12 (40a-40e) have been cut out, stubs remain)
Quire 616 (fols 41-54; last two leaves cancelled, stubs remain)
Quire 712 (fols 55-66)
Quire 812 (fols 67-75; leaves 9-11 have been cut out, stubs remain)
Quire 912 (fols 77-88)
Quire 1012 (fols 89-100)
Quire 1112 + 4 (fols 101-116; 4 additional leaves are inserted between leaf 9 and leaf 10)
Quire 1212 (fols 117-128)
Quire 132 (fols 129-130; the stubs of conjoint leaves are found after fol. 142)
Quire 1412 (fols 131-142)
Quire 1512 (fols 143-154)
Quire 1612 (fols 155-165; leaf 11 is cut out, a stub remains)
Quire 1712 (fols 166-177)
Quire 1812 (fols 178-189)
Quire 1912 (fols 190-201)
Quire 206 (fols 202-204; there are 3 stubs after fol. 204)
4 modern parchment flyleaves

Signatures are found in the central lower margin of the first leaf of certain quires. See, for example, fols 143r and 190r.Catchwords are found occasionally in pen (fol. 100v) or plummet (fol. 142v). In quire 6, the last two leaves are cancelled; a catchword on fol. 54v matches the opening words on fol. 55r.

metadata.label: Classmark
metadata.value: MS Add. 3020

metadata.label: Decoration
metadata.value:
At fol. 12r at the beginning of the main text is a 12-line initial in red and blue with filling and partial borderwork. Major sections and some documents have large (3-, 4- or 5-line) initials, some in two colours. Other documents have 2-line initials in red or blue. Some initials have designs in openwork.


Headings and running titles for the original entries are written in red; capitals are touched in red and some sections have alternating red and blue paragraph marks.

metadata.label: Additions
metadata.value:
A static page marker has been added to fol. 189.

On fol. 11r a seventeenth-century hand has added two inscriptions: "W. Virtue non vi. Mildmay" and "M. Ferende vincam. Westmorland", probably the mottoes of Mildmay Fane, second Earl of Westmorland (1601-1666) and his second wife, Mary.

Occasional marginal notes throughout in a range of later hands.

metadata.label: Subject(s)
metadata.value: Cartularies

metadata.label: Format
metadata.value: Codex

metadata.label: Data Source(s)
metadata.value: The description of the contents of this manuscript was prepared by Dr Sandra Raban. The physical and provenance description draws on the Summary Catalogue of the Additional Medieval Manuscripts in Cambridge University Library acquired before 1940 by Jayne Ringrose (Woodbridge: Boydell, 2009).

metadata.label: Layout
metadata.value:
40 lines per page in the original sections of the text. Evidence of pricking, particularly at the bottom edge of pages. Pages are frame-ruled with ruling for running heads at the top and bottom of each page.

There is greater variation in the layout of the additional sections.

metadata.label: Foliation
metadata.value:
Original foliation of each part in the top corner of both rectos and versos in the same red ink used for rubrics in Roman numerals.

Part 1 i-xvii
part 2 i-ciiii
part 3 i-xxxii

This foliation is often continued for additional material in each part in Roman or Arabic numerals in brown ink or in red and black.

Continuous modern pencil foliation from 1 to 204, omitting 76, in the top right corner of each recto.
